No better place to be a woman than the United States of America. I moved to this incredible country at the age of 10, not speaking a word of English, having said goodbye to my extended family forever. My life hasn’t been easy but because of this land of opportunity I’ve had the privilege to move forward and excel in my career, family, and all other aspirations. Things that would have never been afforded to me if I lived in Iran under the brutal Islamic Republic, where a woman is considered legally one half of a man. Where women just like me don’t have basic human rights. For the last almost 5 months I’ve been overwhelmed with survivor’s guilt knowing that I could have easily been a #mahsaamini #nikashakarami #sarinaesmailzadeh or their sisters or mothers. 
Everything that I have intentionally suppressed for the past 31 years to numb myself from the overwhelming pain of my childhood in Iran, living through the Iran/Iraq war, my parents being imprisoned, not seeing my dad for 6 years, losing my dad and never reconciling our relationship is all bubbling to the surface.  From the beginning of this revolution I have felt the pain of the Iranian people in every part of my being. The pain of the mothers hits home the deepest for me. 
After mulling in this pain, angst, anger and frustration I finally made the decision to acknowledge and step into my power. Redirecting the energy bottled up in me to advocate and be the voice for the voiceless. To get justice for the women, mothers, children, men of my Motherland. 
I’m living proof that there is no limit to what you can achieve, if you believe in your cause and set your mind to it. God bless this nation where you can contact and connect with elected leaders and officials in hopes of bringing about real change. 
In a lot of ways I'm still that helpless 10 year old who had no
control over her formative years as life living in exile was
filled with chaos. This is me, the 41 year old woman, holding
the little girl's hand walking through the halls of congress
trying to correct the mistakes of the past. #iranrevolution #mahsaamini #mahsaact #toomajsalehi
